Such a tutorial wouldn't take away from any of the experience other than the gatekeeping some people seem to love so much. It would help new players to get in the mindset of thinking "why did I die there?" instead of "boss interrupted my heavy attack, this game sucks!" 6/6

The game could have a longer tutorial that explains to players that you can't just wail on an enemy and expect things to go well. It could explain that sure you can dodge attack #1, but follow up attack #2 is going to bite you if you dodge left instead of right 5/

The flip side of this is that Fromsoft games are terrible at actually teaching these principles, and humans are stubborn often tend towards "the thing I want to do doesn't work, this boss is bullshit!" 4/

Playing Elden Ring and not adjusting to the need to defend, dodge, and full-on-retreat sometimes is like playing Pokemon games without paying mind to type advantages/disadvantages, or like playing Smash Bros. and only trying to falcon punch things 3/

Watching clips of new players trying it, they spend most of their time trying to always be attacking rather than finding the balance of attacking when appropriate and defending when appropriate. A lot of games won't punish you for that, Elden Ring absolutely will 2/

Nobody asked but I'm going to weigh in anyways

The thing that new Elden Ring players tend to have in common is that they play the game in a way they think will be fun, rather than a way that works, get punished for it, and have trouble adjusting to what the game demands. 1/
